## A Year of Recalls: 2026 by the Numbers

Did you know that we've already logged 317 food recalls this year and it's only May? That's not a typo. Of these, 87 were classified as Class I -- situations where there is a reasonable probability that the use of the product will cause serious adverse health consequences or death. If that doesn't make you check your pantry twice, consider that last year, categories like Allergens and Foreign Objects had 178 and 80 recalls respectively.

## Repeat Offenders: A Persistent Problem

A total of 66 companies have earned the dubious honor of being repeat offenders in 2026 alone. It's worth mentioning that some of these brands have abysmal track records. Moonlight Packing Corporation, for instance, stands out with an F rating and 11 recalls -- every single one of them Class I. Albertsons Companies LLC is not far behind, with 11 recalls and 10 being Class I. These numbers tell a story of negligence that shouldn't be ignored.

## A Look at Recent Recalls

April 22, 2026, saw a couple of recalls that grabbed our attention. PURE PALM C/O DVD had mislabeled their Coconut Date Bites, and Booey's Gourmet LLC failed to properly declare allergens in its Dragon's Breath sauce. Both cases highlight how critical accurate labeling is for consumer safety, especially for those with severe food allergies.

Then there's Bee Well Honey Farm & Supply Inc., whose honey was found to have a high C4 sugar content. What is C4 sugar, you ask? It's a marker that the product might not be as "100% Pure Honey" as the label suggests.

## What Consumers Can Do

The best way to protect yourself is to stay informed. Consult the FDA's recall database regularly and subscribe to notifications if possible. Always read labels carefully, even if it's a brand you trust. And if something seems fishy (pun intended), err on the side of caution.

## Conclusion: A Call to Responsibility

The data doesn't lie: food safety is an ongoing concern. While regulatory agencies are doing their part to crack down on offenders, the responsibility also lies with companies to uphold the highest standards. As for us, the consumers, vigilance is our best tool.

Here's to hoping the latter half of 2026 sees a significant improvement.
